<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="288" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,151,392]" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,260,285]" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Distribution.</emphasis>
Distributed from 
<collectingCountry box="[553,668,260,285]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[704,818,260,285]" name="Argentina" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, southern 
<collectingCountry box="[933,1001,260,285]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1056,1162,261,285]" name="Paraguay" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">
<collectingRegion box="[1056,1162,261,285]" country="Paraguay" name="Asuncion" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Paraguay</collectingRegion>
</collectingCountry>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,295,320]" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Habitat.</emphasis>
Associated with leaf cutter ants in the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[848,895,296,319]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="288" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[848,895,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="288">Atta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, typically found in the refuse piles or fungus gardens. Some specimens have been collected with flight intercept traps, perhaps indicative of their ability to move between nests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
